<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1919-06-26T18:48:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1919-06-26T18:48:00-05:00" n="362" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d362">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">763.72113/1054: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in Honduras</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Jones</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Tegucigalpa</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1919-06-26T18:00:00-05:48"><hi rend="italic">June 26,
                                        1919, 6 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[<hi rend="italic">Received
                                    June 28, 12.35 p.m.</hi>]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>Your May 26, 6 p.m. I have just received a note from President Bertrand
                            to the effect that no enemy properties have been taken over up to the
                            present time by the Government of Honduras and that inasmuch as Germans
                            here filed protest to declare Honduranean alien property law
                            unconstitutional nothing can be done until the Supreme Court renders its
                            decision. Nothing definite can be obtained either from the President or
                            Alien Property Custodian.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Jones</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>